\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Table tags}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Tables are a bit more difficult to define in XHTML, so I recommend arranging them neatly to avoid getting confused. There are 4 tags for defining tables <table></table>, <tr></tr>, <th></th> and <td></td>.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 <table></table> behaves like a division tag and are the parent tags for the whole table. All table content will go inside these.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 <tr></tr> are the table row tags and define each row.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 <th></th> are the optional table heading tags.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 <td></td> are the table data tags which defines each cell.}
